{
  "In a simple random sample (SRS), every individual has:": "",
  "A probability of 0": "",
  "An equal chance of being selected": "",
  "A guaranteed spot in the sample": "",
  "No chance of selection": "",
  "In an SRS every member of the population has the same probability of being chosen, which is the defining property of simple random sampling.": "",
  "Stratified sampling divides the population into:": "",
  "Paired samples": "",
  "Strata (homogeneous groups)": "",
  "Random groups": "",
  "Clusters": "",
  "Strata are subgroups whose members share similar characteristics, and a random sample is then drawn from each stratum.": "",
  "In cluster sampling, you:": "",
  "Sample one person per group": "",
  "Divide into similar groups": "",
  "Select the first available person": "",
  "Randomly select whole clusters and sample everyone in them": "",
  "Cluster sampling randomly picks entire groups (clusters), and every member within those selected clusters is included in the sample.": "",
  "Systematic sampling selects:": "",
  "The first n individuals on the list": "",
  "Only outliers in the population": "",
  "Random individuals without a pattern": "",
  "Every k-th individual from a list after a random start": "",
  "A random starting point is chosen, and then every k-th individual is selected, where k equals the population size divided by the desired sample size.": "",
  "Convenience sampling is problematic because it:": "",
  "Is too expensive": "",
  "Produces too much data": "",
  "Requires stratification": "",
  "Introduces selection bias": "",
  "Convenience samples over-represent easily accessible individuals and systematically exclude hard-to-reach parts of the population.": "",
