  "Combines multiple sampling methods in successive stages": "",
  "Uses only one method throughout": "",
  "Is the same as SRS": "",
  "Is always biased": "",
  "Multi-stage sampling applies different sampling techniques at each level, such as first selecting clusters and then taking an SRS within each cluster.": "",
  "What is a sampling frame?": "",
  "The margin of error of a survey": "",
  "The list of all individuals from which the sample is drawn": "",
  "The population parameter being estimated": "",
  "The sample itself": "",
  "A sampling frame is the complete list of population members that are eligible for selection; ideally it matches the entire target population.": "",
  "What does undercoverage mean in sampling?": "",
  "The sample is too large": "",
  "Too many strata are created": "",
  "The response rate is 100%": "",
  "Some population members are missing from the sampling frame": "",
  "Undercoverage occurs when certain groups in the population are not represented in the sampling frame, leading to potential bias.": "",
  "What is a voluntary response sample?": "",
  "A perfectly representative sample": "",
  "A stratified sample with volunteers in each stratum": "",
  "A sample where participants self-select to participate": "",
  "A type of SRS": "",
  "In a voluntary response sample, people choose whether to respond, which tends to over-represent those with strong opinions.": "",
  "What does 'probability sampling' mean?": "",
  "The researcher picks whoever is available": "",
  "Members are selected based on convenience": "",
  "Only volunteers are included": "",
  "Every member has a known, non-zero chance of being selected": "",
  "Probability sampling requires that every member of the population has a known, positive probability of selection, enabling valid statistical inference.": "",
  "What is the sampling interval in systematic sampling?": "",
  "The number of strata": "",
  "The total number of clusters": "",
  "The value k = population size / sample size used to select every k-th individual": "",
  "The confidence level of the study": "",
  "The sampling interval k is calculated by dividing the population size N by the desired sample size n, and then every k-th individual is selected.": "",
  "What is meant by a 'representative sample'?": "",
  "A sample chosen by an expert": "",
  "A sample that includes every population member": "",
  "A sample that mirrors the key characteristics of the population": "",
  "A sample with the largest possible size": "",
  "A representative sample accurately reflects the demographics and attributes of the population, allowing generalizations to be made.": "",
  "What is proportionate stratified sampling?": "",
  "Equal numbers are taken from each stratum regardless of stratum size": "",
  "Only the largest stratum is sampled": "",
  "The sample size from each stratum is proportional to the stratum's share of the population": "",
  "Clusters replace strata": "",
  "In proportionate stratified sampling, each stratum contributes to the sample in proportion to its size in the overall population.": "",
