  "Variability within a single data point": "",
  "Sampling variability is the natural variation in statistics from sample to sample; it decreases as sample size increases.": "",
  "A school district wants to survey parents about a new lunch program. They divide parents by school (elementary, middle, high) and randomly select 50 parents from each school level. What sampling method is this?": "",
  "The school levels serve as strata (homogeneous groups), and a random sample is drawn from each one, making this stratified sampling.": "",
  "A researcher studying factory workers lists all 5,000 employees, randomly picks a number between 1 and 25, and then selects every 25th person. If the random start is employee 14, the sample includes employees 14, 39, 64, 89, and so on. What type of sampling is this?": "",
  "Choosing a random start and then selecting every k-th individual (here k = 25) is the definition of systematic sampling. The sample size will be 5,000/25 = 200.": "",
  "A health agency wants to study nutrition habits across a large country. They randomly select 20 towns and survey every household in those towns. What sampling method is being used?": "",
  "The towns are naturally occurring clusters; randomly selecting entire towns and surveying all households within them is cluster sampling.": "",
  "A university assigns each of its 30,000 students a number and uses a computer random number generator to select 500 students for a satisfaction survey. What type of sampling is this?": "",
  "Simple random sampling (SRS)": "",
  "Each student has an equal and independent chance of being selected through the random number generator, which is the definition of an SRS.": "",
  "A marketing firm wants to survey shoppers at a mall. They stand by the entrance and ask the first 100 people who walk by. A critic argues the results are not generalizable. Why?": "",
  "This is convenience sampling, which introduces selection bias": "",
  "They should have used a smaller sample": "",
  "Mall shoppers are always representative": "",
  "Sampling only people who happen to pass by a specific entrance is convenience sampling, which systematically excludes people who enter elsewhere or shop at other times.": "",
  "A polling company wants to estimate voter preferences in a state with 10 congressional districts. They randomly select 3 districts, then randomly select 200 registered voters within each selected district. What sampling method is this?": "",
  "Single-stage cluster sampling": "",
  "Multi-stage sampling": "",
  "This is multi-stage sampling because it first randomly selects clusters (districts) and then takes an SRS within each selected cluster.": "",
  "A hospital has 800 nurses working in three shifts: day (400), evening (250), and night (150). A researcher uses stratified sampling and selects 10% from each shift. How many nurses are in the sample?": "",
  "40 day + 25 evening + 15 night = 80 total": "",
  "80 from each shift = 240 total": "",
  "All 800 nurses": "",
  "30 from each shift = 90 total": "",
  "Taking 10% from each stratum gives 0.10 x 400 = 40, 0.10 x 250 = 25, and 0.10 x 150 = 15, for a total of 80 nurses.": "",
  "A city has 200 apartment buildings. A researcher randomly selects 10 buildings and surveys every tenant in those buildings. She finds that average rent in the sample is higher than the city average. What is the most likely explanation?": "",
  "Cluster sampling always overestimates the mean": "",
  "She used too many clusters": "",
  "The cluster sample happened to select more expensive buildings by chance": "",
  "The result is impossible with cluster sampling": "",
  "Cluster sampling can produce estimates that differ from the population value because entire clusters may be more or less expensive; sampling variability between clusters is a known limitation.": "",
  "A population of 10,000 is listed alphabetically. A systematic sample with k = 50 and a random start of 23 would include individuals 23, 73, 123, ... What is the total sample size?": "",
  "250": "",
  "500": "",
  "100": "",
  "200": "",
  "The sample size is N/k = 10,000/50 = 200. Starting at 23, the sequence is 23, 73, 123, ... up to 9,973, giving exactly 200 individuals.": "",
  "A national education study first divides schools into urban, suburban, and rural categories. Then within each category, 15 schools are randomly chosen, and all students in those schools are surveyed. What combination of sampling methods is used?": "",
  "Systematic sampling only": "",
  "Cluster sampling followed by stratified sampling": "",
  "Simple random sampling only": "",
  "Stratified sampling followed by cluster sampling": "",
  "The categories (urban, suburban, rural) act as strata, and within each stratum whole schools are selected as clusters, making this a stratified-then-cluster multi-stage design.": ""
